notes.text: The traditional view is that the adverb only should be placed next to the word or words whose meaning it restricts: I have seen him only once rather than I have only seen him once. The argument for this, a topic which has occupied grammarians for more than 200 years, is that if only is not placed correctly the scope or emphasis is wrong, and could even result in ambiguity. But in normal, everyday English, the impulse is to state only as early as possible in the sentence, generally just before the verb. The result is, in fact, hardly ever ambiguous: few native speakers would be confused by the sentence I have only seen him once, and the supposed ‘logical’ sense often emerges only with further clarification, as in I've only seen him once, but I've heard him many times

definitions: an interval spanning six consecutive notes in a diatonic major or minor scale, e.g. C to A (major sixth) or A to F (minor sixth).

etymologies: late Middle English (denoting the time during which something, especially a disease, runs its course): from Old French periode, via Latin from Greek periodos ‘orbit, recurrence, course’, from peri- ‘around’ + hodos ‘way, course’. The sense ‘portion of time’ dates from the early 17th century

definitions: a length or portion of time

examples.text: he had long periods of depression
the period 1977–85
the training period is between 16 and 18 months

definitions: a portion of time in the life of a nation, civilization, etc. characterized by the same prevalent features or conditions

examples.text: the early medieval period

shortDefinitions: portion of time in life of nation etc.

definitions: a major division of geological time that is a subdivision of an era and is itself subdivided into epochs

examples.text: the Cretaceous period

definitions: each of the set divisions of the day in a school allocated to a lesson or other activity

definitions: each of the divisions of the playing time of a sporting event

definitions: the interval of time between successive occurrences of the same state in an oscillatory or cyclic phenomenon, such as a mechanical vibration, an alternating current, a variable star, or an electromagnetic wave.

definitions: the time taken by a celestial object to rotate about its axis, or to make one circuit of its orbit.

definitions: the interval between successive equal values of a periodic function.

definitions: a flow of blood and other material from the lining of the uterus, occurring in non-pregnant women at intervals of about 28 days between puberty and the menopause and typically lasting for a few days
